instance virtual_to_physical_interaction : DTDFVocab:VirtualToPhysical [
    base:desc "Control commands originate from the digital twin’s controller component. The controller publishes fan and heatbed control messages to the same RabbitMQ broker. The low‑level driver subscribes to these messages, translates them into GPIO signals via optocouplers and MOSFETs, and actuates the fan and heatbed accordingly. The documents do not describe message validation, authentication, or explicit feedback mechanisms beyond the driver’s periodic polling of sensor data."
]

instance twinning_time_scale : DTDFVocab:TimeScale [
    base:desc "The digital twin synchronizes with the physical twin through RabbitMQ messages. The low‑level driver polls the DS18S20 temperature sensors and checks for commands from the controller in a periodic loop (period not explicitly specified). The controller processes incoming temperature measurements and issues heating/fan commands immediately after each measurement. The DT streams the received messages to a time‑series database for real‑time visualization on a dashboard. No explicit latency or sampling‑rate requirements are stated in the documents."
]

instance dt_constellation : DTDFVocab:Constellation [
    base:desc "The DT is built around a message‑oriented middleware (RabbitMQ, AMQP) that connects the physical controller, low‑level driver, and digital‑twin services. The controller on the Raspberry Pi listens for temperature measurements and publishes control commands. The low‑level driver reads the DS18S20 sensors, enforces a safe protocol, and forwards data to RabbitMQ. Digital‑twin services subscribe to these messages: a real‑time dashboard consumes the data stream; a calibration service runs the Model B parameter estimation; a Kalman‑filter module estimates the unmeasured heat‑bed temperature; a co‑simulation engine performs what‑if analyses; and a self‑adaptation orchestrator schedules experiments, re‑calibrates, and reconfigures the controller. All services share the same RabbitMQ broker and a common time‑series database for persistence."
]

instance fidelity_and_validity_considerations : DTDFVocab:FidelityConsideration [
    base:desc "Model fidelity is ensured through a dedicated calibration experiment that generates a temperature trajectory used to fit the free parameters of Models A and B. Validation is performed by comparing model predictions to measured data (Figure 13), demonstrating that Model B better captures the heatbed’s thermal inertia. Uncertainty is implicitly addressed by the Kalman filter, which estimates the heatbed temperature and flags anomalies. Error detection is achieved via the Kalman filter’s residual analysis, and corrective actions are taken by the self‑adaptation loop: upon detecting a change in plant behavior, the DT schedules a new experiment, recalibrates Model B, updates the Kalman filter, runs what‑if simulations to optimize controller parameters, and re‑configures the controller. Quality assurance is supported by real‑time monitoring, anomaly detection, and the iterative calibration–simulation–control cycle."
]

instance dt_technical_connection : DTDFVocab:TechnicalConnection [
    base:desc "The system’s communication backbone is a RabbitMQ message broker deployed on the Raspberry Pi 4. The broker implements the AMQP protocol (version not specified). The controller and low‑level driver communicate with the broker over the local network (Wi‑Fi or Ethernet) using the standard RabbitMQ client libraries. No details on network topology, bandwidth, latency, redundancy, or security mechanisms are provided in the documents."
]

instance dt_hosting_deployment : DTDFVocab:Deployment [
    base:desc "All digital twin components (controller, low‑level driver, RabbitMQ broker) run on a single Raspberry Pi 4 Model B, which is an on‑premise edge device. The documents do not specify CPU model, RAM, storage, or scalability provisions. The deployment is a single‑node, on‑premise installation without explicit redundancy or high‑availability mechanisms."
]

instance horizontal_integration : DTDFVocab:HoriIntegration [
    base:desc "External integration is achieved via the open‑source RabbitMQ broker (AMQP protocol) and a time‑series database (type not specified). The repository at https://github.com/INTO‑CPS‑Association/example‑incubator hosts the hardware and software specifications, enabling other systems to clone and deploy the same stack. No additional enterprise integration patterns or interoperability standards are mentioned."
]

instance security_and_safety_considerations : DTDFVocab:SecuritySafety [
    base:desc "Safe protocol incorporated into the low‑level driver to keep the device in a safe state. The driver periodically reads temperature data, checks for controller commands via the RabbitMQ communication server, and uploads data to the server. No explicit cybersecurity protocols, access control mechanisms, authentication systems, or threat mitigation strategies are described in the documents."
]